First Read: 14-Jan-26
HB226 Enrolled
1 Enrolled, An Act,
2
3 Relating to crimes and offenses; to amend Section
4 13A-5-9, Code of Alabama 1975, to further provide for the
5 meaning of nolo contendere pleas for purposes of the habitual
6 offender law.
7 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
8 Section 1. Section 13A-5-9, Code of Alabama 1975, is
9 amended to read as follows:
10 "§13A-5-9
11 (a) In all cases when it is shown that a criminal
12 defendant has been previously convicted of a Class A, Class B,
13 or Class C felony and after the conviction has committed
14 another Class A, Class B, or Class C felony, he or she must be
15 punished as follows:
16 (1) On conviction of a Class C felony, he or she must
17 be punished for a Class B felony.
18 (2) On conviction of a Class B felony, he or she must
19 be punished for a Class A felony.
20 (3) On conviction of a Class A felony, he or she must
21 be punished by imprisonment for life or for any term of not
22 more than 99 years but not less than 15 years.
23 (b) In all cases when it is shown that a criminal
24 defendant has been previously convicted of any two felonies
25 that are Class A, Class B, or Class C felonies and after such
26 convictions has committed another Class A, Class B, or Class C
27 felony, he or she must be punished as follows:
28 (1) On conviction of a Class C felony, he or she must
Page 1

(1) On conviction of a Class C felony, he or she must
HB226 Enrolled
29 be punished for a Class A felony.
30 (2) On conviction of a Class B felony, he or she must
31 be punished by imprisonment for life or for any term of not
32 more than 99 years but not less than 15 years.
33 (3) On conviction of a Class A felony, he or she must
34 be punished by imprisonment for life or for any term of not
35 less than 99 years.
36 (c) In all cases when it is shown that a criminal
37 defendant has been previously convicted of any three felonies
38 that are Class A, Class B, or Class C felonies and after such
39 convictions has committed another Class A, Class B, or Class C
40 felony, he or she must be punished as follows:
41 (1) On conviction of a Class C felony, he or she must
42 be punished by imprisonment for life or for any term of not
43 more than 99 years but not less than 15 years.
44 (2) On conviction of a Class B felony, he or she must
45 be punished by imprisonment for life or any term of not less
46 than 20 years.
47 (3) On conviction of a Class A felony, where the
48 defendant has no prior convictions for any Class A felony, he
49 or she must be punished by imprisonment for life or life
50 without the possibility of parole, in the discretion of the
51 trial court.
52 (4) On conviction of a Class A felony, where the
53 defendant has one or more prior convictions for any Class A
54 felony, he or she must be punished by imprisonment for life
55 without the possibility of parole.
56 (d) In all cases when it is shown that a criminal
Page 2

(d) In all cases when it is shown that a criminal
HB226 Enrolled
57 defendant has been previously convicted of any two or more
58 felonies that are Class A or Class B felonies and after such
59 convictions has committed a Class D felony, upon conviction,
60 he or she must be punished for a Class C felony.
61 (e) In all cases when it is shown that a criminal
62 defendant has been previously convicted of any three or more
63 felonies and after such convictions has committed a Class D
64 felony, upon conviction, he or she must be punished for a
65 Class C felony.
66 (f) For purposes of this section, "convicted" includes
67 any conviction from this state or out of this state, and a
68 conviction based on a plea of nolo contendere, a plea of no
69 contest, a best interests plea, or an Alford plea shall be
70 treated in the same manner as a conviction based on a plea of
71 guilty unless any of the foregoing pleas has been expunged."
72 Section 2. This act shall become effective on October
73 1, 2026.
